Small space rodents. Evolved on a significantly larger planet with slightly higher gravity, meaning that they were constrained to their planet until their technology developed quite a bit, unlike humans on Earth who could get to orbit with relatively simple rocketry systems. They would need to build infrastructure to help them get to orbit. They take things more slow and steady all around. Thanks to their small size, cryopreservation is significantly easier for them. As such, by the time they get to space they already what are for them fairly mature stasis systems. They make use of these on all long journeys, even interplanetary. After their propulsion systems mature more, they begin to send slowboat sleeper ships on interstellar journeys. These rodent people slowly but steadily spread across the stars, colonizing many planets in what would otherwise be a rough coalition of worlds, were it not for their great natural stability and cohesion. As a result of that, they function as autonomous regions that all still serve the greater purpose of their people and homeworld, with no breakaways, revolts, or seriously divergent cultures.
Humans, on the other hand, play much more fast and loose. They live and breathe chaos by the standards of the rodent people. They invented warp drives and travel the stars little different to how they traveled their own seas. Eventually the two meet and it's a first contact and culture clash story from there. That and the rodent people wanting to get their paws on warp drives as it would allow them to have a properly unified empire.
